1D Time Series
Data: A single variable measured over time (e.g., daily temperature, stock closing price).
This is a 1D dataset because the independent axis is just time.

2D Scalar Field
Data: A scalar (single value) at each point in a 2D space (e.g., heatmap of temperature across a city).
This is 2D because the independent axes are x and y (location).

3D Scalar Field
Data: A scalar value at each point in a 3D volume (e.g., air pressure inside a room).
This is 3D because the independent axes are x, y, z (spatial coordinates).

2D Vector Field
Data: A 2D space where each point has a vector (e.g., wind flow over a map, with direction + magnitude).
This is 2D because the independent axes are x and y, but each has a vector output.

3D Shape
Data: Geometric data describing the shape of an object in 3D (e.g., CT scan, CAD model).
This is 3D because the data encodes x, y, z coordinates of surfaces/volumes.

Graph (not a tree)
Data: Nodes and edges forming arbitrary connections (e.g., social network, transportation graph).
This is a graph structure since it can contain cycles and complex links, not just parent-child.
